  "diary": "Started the morning like always—Miso got her breakfast, I got my tea by the window. The light was soft and nice. Walked over to Gas Works Park while the city was still quiet; fed the ducks some bread and just sat there with my journal for a bit, watching the water. There's something about that park that settles me. The library branch was calling my name, so I stopped by and picked up a new mystery. The librarians there still remember me, which feels good. Hit QFC for salmon and vegetables—had a nice chat with one of the cashiers about her garden. Spent the afternoon at home the way I like it: reading, journaling, listening to some music by the window. Made a decent salmon dinner. The whole day had this gentle rhythm to it, nothing rushed. Even with the transit strike happening out there, I barely noticed it. Just stayed in my neighborhood, moving at my own pace.",
  "thought_process": "The strike didn't really touch me today—I'm walking distance from everything I need in Wallingford, and at my age, I'm not in a hurry anyway. That freed something up mentally. I chose to lean into the routine that makes me happiest: the ducks, the library, simple food, time with my thoughts. There was no friction today, no need to problem-solve or adapt. I think I'm at a point in life where I've figured out what I actually need versus what I thought I needed when I was working. The neighborhood is my library now. I stayed close to home because it felt right, not because I was trapped. That's the difference.",
